<div class="timeline">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-xs-12">
			<div class="entryGroup">
				<span class="entryGroupHead">2016</span>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">January 2016:</span> Penalty phase trial is scheduled to begin Jan 4 for Wozniak, who faces a possible death sentence.</div>
			</div>
			<div class="entryGroup">
				<span class="entryGroupHead">2015</span>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">December 2015:</span> Superior Court Judge Richard King rules the District Attorney <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/king-695531-goethals-cases.html">practice of “blanket papering” Judge Goethals</a> has “substantially disrupted the orderly administration of criminal justice in Orange County, the sixth-largest county in the nation.” Rackauckas <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/goethals-696685-king-county.html">files an appeal challenging King’s decision</a>.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">December 2015:</span> After <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/herr-695023-wozniak-kibuishi.html">five years of delays</a>, trial begins <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/herr-695495-wozniak-police.html">for community theater actor Wozniak</a>, accused of killing two people -- dismembering one of them -- in a plot to steal money. He is <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/wozniak-696422-herr-phase.html">convicted of first-degree murder</a> of neighbor Samuel Herr, 26, and Herr’s friend, 23-year-old Juri “Julie” Kibuishi.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">November 2015:</span> More than three dozen prominent legal experts, including former California Attorney General John Van de Kamp and former Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti, <a href="http://files.onset.freedom.com/ocregister/docs/Request_for_Federal_Investigation_in_Orange_County_11.17.15.pdf">write a letter to U.S. Attorney General Loretta Lynch</a> to declare a “crisis” in the Orange County justice system. They call <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/orange-692665-attorney-county.html">for a U.S. Justice Department investigation</a>.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">November 2015:</span> Superior Court Judge Richard King <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/ortiz-692758-deputies-case.html">grants a retrial for Eric Ortiz</a>, a gang member convicted in January of killing a Santa Ana man in 2006:. King finds Ortiz cannot receive a fair hearing after four sheriff’s deputies <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/attorney-688078-case-deputies.html">invoke their Fifth Amendment rights and decline to testify</a>.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">October 2015:</span> Superior Court Judge John D. Conley <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/judge-690042-sanders-wozniak.html">rejects defense allegations of prosecutorial misconduct</a> in handling of the Wozniak double-murder case, clearing the way for the death penalty trial to begin. </div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">September 2015:</span> Deputy District Attorney Erik Petersen, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/petersen-681635-attorney-district.html">once a rising star in Mexican Mafia prosecutions, resigns</a>. He handled three of four criminal cases that fell apart due to use of jailhouse informants and the withholding of evidence. “Petersen’s tendency to not make (confidential informant) discovery until 30 days before trial creates problems,” prosecutor Dan Wagner wrote in an email to colleagues.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">July 2015:</span> Rackauckas says he will assemble a committee of legal experts <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/use-670384-informants-attorney.html">to review his office’s use of jailhouse informants</a>. </div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">March 2015:</span> In a move that stuns prosecutors, Goethals reverses course <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/attorney-654000-county-case.html">and removes all 250 lawyers in the District Attorney’s Office from the Dekraai case</a>. The judge’s decision says the Seal Beach shooter is unlikely to receive a fair penalty phase trial unless local prosecutors are ousted. He concludes two sheriff’s deputies “either intentionally lied or willfully withheld material evidence’ about records used to track movements of jail informants. </div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">January 2015:</span> Sanders accuses local prosecutors and police of misusing jailhouse informants in other cases and <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/sanders-649230-murphy-wozniak.html">moves to block the death penalty </a>against a second high-profile defendant, Daniel Wozniak. The community theater actor is accused of killing two acquaintances – beheading one of them – in 2010:.</div>
			</div>
			<div class="entryGroup">
				<span class="entryGroupHead">2014</span>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">December 2014:</span> Orange County Sheriff Sandra Hutchens <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/informants-644455-hutchens-sanders.html">concedes her department could have benefited from better organization</a> and training of jail deputies in how to handle informants. “We didn’t have a comprehensive plan for handling informants ... We do now.”</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">November 2014:</span> Register report details how two jail informants, both members of the Mexican Mafia, lived like kings in custody, including cable TV in their cells and Del Taco food delivered by officers. The pair received more than <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/cuevas-643108-paredes-informants.html">$150,000 in payments</a> from law enforcement agencies during an 18-month period.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">August 2014:</span> Superior Court Judge Thomas M. Goethals concludes <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/dekraai-630582-judge-prosecutors.html">prosecutors were negligent but not malicious</a> when they failed to turn over evidence to the defense. The judge denies a defense request to take the death penalty off the table for Dekraai. D.A. Tony Rackauckas acknowledges his office made mistakes, but says they were unintentional.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">May 2014:</span> Dekraai <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/dekraai-612380-salon-shot.html">pleads guilty to eight counts of murder</a>.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">April 2014:</span> Prosecutors <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/dekraai-610894-attorney-court.html">agree not to use the jailhouse recordings </a>after Dekraai’s defense contends authorities improperly obtained the information.</div>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">January 2014:</span> Sanders files a <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/sanders-684780-attorney-case.html">505-page legal motion, with 15,000 page of supporting documents</a>, alleging an orchestrated effort by prosecutors and police to place known jail informants in proximity to Dekraai and other high-value defendants.</div>
			</div>
			<div class="entryGroup">
				<span class="entryGroupHead">2013</span>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">January 2013:</span> Prosecutors file documents saying they plan to use secret jailhouse recordings of Dekraai describing the shootings as evidence during trial. Dekraai defense also receives records on cases in which Perez was an informant. </div>
			</div>
			<div class="entryGroup">
				<span class="entryGroupHead">2012</span>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">Summer 2012:</span> Discovery documents provided to the defense identify the jailhouse informant only as “Inmate F.” Dekraai’s defense attorney, however, doesn’t find out informant Fernando Perez’s identity until summer of 2012:, eight months after more than 100 hours of tapes were recorded. Assistant Public Defender Scott Sanders also learns that the same jail informant spoke with another high-profile client: <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/herr-356467-wozniak-grand.html">double murder suspect Daniel Wozniak</a>.</div>
			</div>
			<div class="entryGroup">
				<span class="entryGroupHead">2011</span>
				<div class="entry"><span class="entryHead">October 2011:</span> Three days after his arrest, Dekraai is moved to a psychiatric evaluation area inside the county lockup, where he is befriended <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/perez-603893-motion-dekraai.html">by a jailhouse informant, Fernando Perez</a>, in the cell next door. Orange County Sheriff’s deputies then wire Dekraai’s cell <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/informants-693296-attorney-dekraai.html">to secretly record their conversations</a>. </div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>


